        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#VM">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost">ἀνφο</supplied>τέροισι θεοῖ<supplied reason="lost">σι</supplied>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>λ<unclear>κα</unclear><gap reason="lost" quantity="1" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text after Arena 1989 (IGASM I)</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <note>Guarducci (1967): [h]ε̄́ρο̄ισι θεοῖ[ς</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <note>Gallavotti: [hυπερ]<unclear>τ</unclear>έροισι or [hυψι]<unclear>τ</unclear>έροισι or [ἀνφο]<unclear>τ</unclear>έροισι θεο<unclear>ῖ</unclear>[σι] or [h]ιεροῖσι (θεο̄ν)</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <note>Manni Piraino: --]γ<unclear>υ</unclear>[--</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <note>Johnston (1975): [ἀνέθ]<unclear>εκε</unclear></note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <note>Gallavotti: [hυ]<unclear>β</unclear>λ<unclear>α</unclear>[ῖος</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>[---] in honour of/to both gods [---]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>[---] in onore di/a entrambi gli dei [---]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>From the meagre fragments of the epigraph, Gallavotti hypothesises that it may be a dedication to the Dioscuri (on whose cult in Megara Iblea see Pareti 1920). 
                    Manni Piraino ascribes the alphabetical features to the Argolis area and Arena suggests, based on a hypothetical reconstruction of the second part of the text as ἀντ’ἀλκᾶς
                    (therefore in Doric dialect), that the inscription can be ascribed to western Argolis. If the hypothesis of reconstruction as ἀλκά ('valiant, courageous', a rare word used in poetry, cf. e.g. h.Hom.28.3, Pi.O.9.72) 
                    were correct, one might think, especially given the dactylic incipit of the first part of the text, that it is a poetic text.</p>
            </div>
